  "explanation": "The claim that quitting social media for 12 months transforms your life is unsupported at its stated magnitude. RCT evidence (Allcott et al. 2020, Hunt et al. 2018) shows statistically significant but modest well-being improvements (~0.09–0.15 SD), not dramatic transformation. The narrative suffers from high smoothness, substantial silent evidence (survivorship bias excludes relapsers, isolators, and career-damaged quitters), and unacknowledged fat-tail downside risks including absorbing-barrier network decay in professional fields. The sign of the intervention is probably correct for most people, but the magnitude is overstated, the replacement activity (not the quit itself) is the likely causal lever, and no one selling the quit bears the downside.",
